Variables:

We will be looking at how time spent on different categories of travel affects sleep, so we have listed the 6 digit (TRCODEP) code for sleep along with the 4 digit (TRTIER2P) codes of each category of travel, each starting with 18 to indicate traveling for that reason.

  • 010101 sleeping
  • 18 travel:
    • 1801 personal care
    • 1802 household activities
    • 1803 travel related to caring for household members
    • 1804 travel related to caring for nonhousehold members
    • 1805 work
    • 1806 education
    • 1807 consumer purchases
    • 1808 using professional and personal care services
    • 1809 household services
    • 1810 using government services and civic obligations
    • 1811 eating and drinking
    • 1812 socializing relaxing leisure
    • 1813 sports exercise recreation
    • 1814 religious/spiritual
    • 1815 volunteer
    • 1816 phone calls
    • 1818 security procedures related to traveling
    • 1899 nec

First, we filter our variables of interest from the atus data and select columns we need (i.e we did not include things like if a child was with you and where you were during the activity). We have called this shortened data frame atus_main

atus_main <- atus %>%
  filter(TRCODEP == 010101 | TRTIER1P == 18 | TRTIER2P == 0201 | TRTIER2P == 0501 |
          TRTIER2P == 0601 | TRTIER2P == 1203 ) %>%
  dplyr::select(TUCASEID, TRCODEP, TRTIER1P, TRTIER2P, TUACTDUR)

We are going to determine how many hours were spent for each travel related activity across households. We predict that the most time spent traveling will be related to work, education, and caring for household members.

travel_sum <- atus_travel %>% 
  group_by(TRTIER2P) %>% 
  summarise(min=sum(as.numeric(TUACTDUR)))  %>% 
  mutate(hours=min/60)


head(travel_sum)

This bar chart is a visualization of total hours spent for each travel activity across all households. Overall, the most time spent traveling is for consumer purchases. The second most is time spent traveling is for work followed by socializing and leisure.

Plot of Consumer Purchases on Sleep (1807)

reg_1807 <- left_join(atus_1807, atus_sleep, by = "TUCASEID")
head(reg_1807)
## # A tibble: 6  3
##   TUCASEID       sum_1807 sum_sleep
##   <I<chr>>          <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 20030100013352       10       905
## 2 20030100014209       20       672
## 3 20030100014550       20       825
## 4 20030100014758       30       180
## 5 20030100015106        5       725
## 6 20030100015322       10       936
reg_1807 %>% ggplot(aes(x= sum_1807, y= sum_sleep)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

There is a slight negative relationship between the variables, so we will make a linear model.

travel_1807_mod <- lm(sum_sleep~sum_1807, data = reg_1807)
summary(travel_1807_mod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = sum_sleep ~ sum_1807, data = reg_1807)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -681.92 -113.66   -2.25  104.71 1143.43

##               0.5 %      99.5 %
## sum_1807 -0.0985558 -0.03186303

We are 99% confident that the coefficient for 1807 (consumer purchases) is between -0.0985558 and -0.03186303. The 99% confidence interval does not contain 0, so we are 99% sure that there is a small negative effect.

Now we will run a model with both 1805 (work) and 1807 (consumer purchases)

travel_full_reg<- reg_1805 %>% left_join(reg_1807)
## Joining, by = c("TUCASEID", "sum_sleep")
na.omit(travel_full_reg)

## sum_1805 -0.5118716 -0.3629791
confint(travel_full_mod, "sum_1807", data = travel_full_reg, level = 0.99 )
##               0.5 %    99.5 %
## sum_1807 -0.3484959 -0.172871

Both coefficients have very low p-values and are significant. We are 99% confident that the 1805 (work) coefficient is between -0.5118716 and -0.3629791 and that the 1807 (consumer purchases) coefficient is between -0.3484959 and -0.172871. Therefore, we are 99% confident that both variables have a negative effect on sleep time.
